0.title: Course Information

1.body: CSC110 is an introduction to programming using the Java programming language and the Jshell REPL. The primary focus of this class is developing problem-solving skills and a general knowledge of programming that will be useful to you in most programming languages. While we will spend a lot of time learning about Java and how to write good code, writing code isn't our ultimate goal. The most important skill you can learn in this class is how to think like a programmer. Once you've mastered that, writing code is surprisingly easy. This syllabus also covers any sections of CSC110L that I am teaching this semester. Policies specific to CSC110L are in the lab section of this syllabus. If you are taking the lab with a different instructor, then refer to their lab syllabus.
1.title: Description

10.body: The course schedule will have the agenda for each class meeting, and all activities and material from class will be posted online. If you want me to cover a specific topic or spend more time on something, then let me know and I will try to fit it into the agenda for an upcoming class. My goal this semester is to run CSC110 as a "flipped" class. Rather than giving traditional lectures during class, material will be introduced outside of class with videos and reading assignments. Class meetings will instead focus on practice activities, projects, and reviews. If I'm not able to prepare sufficient material later in the semester, or if this structure doesn't work for us, then we may switch back to a more traditional structure with in-class lectures. You should show up to each class prepared for what we're doing that day, which means completing any reading or other homework assignments before class starts. Showing up to a group activity unprepared is disrespectful to the people you are working with and may delay starting the activity.
10.title: Class Structure

11.body: You should attend class whenever possible, but you do not need my permission to miss class or leave early. You also don't need to explain absences to me. However, I would appreciate knowing what's going on if you have to miss multiple classes in a row or are absent frequently. The university expects me to contact your academic advisor when you have excessive or consecutive unexcused absences. If you are feeling sick or suspect you may have COVID, the flu, or another contagious illness, then please stay home and focus on recovering. You will be okay if you miss a few classes, and you're not likely to get much out of class while you aren't feeling well. Attending class while sick also poses a risk to everyone else.
11.title: Attendance Policy

13.body: Video Lessons : Professor Blake and I are creating video lessons to cover most of the topics in this class. These are intended to introduce topics and prepare you for in-class activities. Class Activities/Examples : We will have practice activities during class, coding demonstrations, and reviews in which I show solutions to previous activities. Any examples that I create during class will be posted online after the meeting. Notes : I'm in the process of revising my notes for this class, and they will be updated frequently during the semester. I use the notes for reading assignments after we've covered a topic in class. Textbooks : You do not need to purchase any textbooks for this class. I try to cover everything in my notes, but you may want to use a textbook for further reading or to see a different explanation of a topic. I've linked two free textbooks from libretexts.org below. I may also use these for reading assignments if I'm behind on my notes: Programming and Computation Fundamentals, by Busbee and Braunschweig Computer Science from the Bottom Up, by Wienand
13.title: Primary Resources

14.body: Text Editors : You need a text editor to edit code (Microsoft Word and Google Docs are not text editors). I've listed a few suggestions below, but there are many other options out there. It does not matter to me which editor you use as long as you learn how to use it. VS Code : I believe this is the most popular editor currently available. I recommend using it unless you have a good reason to go with another editor. One caveat: I do not personally use VS Code, and I cannot provide much technical support for it. However, due to its popularity you should be able to find plenty of resources online. Notepad++ : I like Notepad++, but it's Windows only and I haven't used it in years. It still appears to be receiving regular updates, so it should be a reasonable choice if you're using Windows and don't like VS Code. Neovim : This is the editor I use. It's harder to learn than the other options in this list, but it's powerful and highly configurable. If you don't mind spending time learning vim motions and various keyboard shortcuts, then it might be worth giving neovim a try. You could also consider vim and emacs , both of which have similar pros and cons to neovim. However, I think most people will be happier with VS Code, so I don't recommend these options unless one appeals to you and you're fine with the learning curve. Java : This is the programming language we're using. You'll set up Java during the first lab, and I'll post directions on Blackboard in case you need to reinstall it in the future. Git Bash : We'll use a terminal regularly. I don't like the default terminal programs on Windows (cmd and Powershell), and some of the scripts and commands I give you will not work in either of them. Git for Windows comes with a decent bash emulator, and I highly recommend it over cmd and Powershell if you use Windows. If you're using a Mac or Linux computer, then the default terminal program (usually bash or zsh) is fine. diagrams.net : This is a web app for creating flowcharts and other diagrams. It can also integrate with Google Drive and allow multiple people to edit the same diagram, but some students have reported issues with lag while doing this.
14.title: Software

15.body: The Java API is a useful reference. It may be intimidating right now, but the more you learn about Java and programming in general, the more easily you'll be able to navigate the API and use it to look up information. Finally, asking good questions is one of the most useful skills you can have as a student. In my experience, most people (myself included) don't ask questions as often as they should, and it can be difficult to ask a question that will quickly lead to a helpful answer. I think the blog posts below provide excellent advice for asking and answering questions: https://jvns.ca/blog/good-questions/ https://jvns.ca/blog/2021/10/21/how-to-get-useful-answers-to-your-questions/ https://jvns.ca/blog/answer-questions-well/
15.title: Other Resources

17.body: I will assign several projects during the semester, and I've created a separate website covering the details of these projects. Each project falls into one of the following categories: A Guided Project provides step-by-step instructions for writing a program. These steps won't tell you exactly what to code, but they break the program into a series of smaller problems that you can solve one at a time. An Expanded Project builds on previous Guided Projects to create a more complete program. It is significantly more complex than a Guided Project, and you will not be given step-by-step directions for completing each task. You also have the option to propose an alternative version of the assignment. A Self-Directed Project requires you to design your own program and submit a proposal describing it. Self-Directed Projects are optional and can be used to replace any of the other projects.
17.title: Projects

18.body: All projects must be submitted on Blackboard, and most projects must pass a set of tests to be considered complete. To make it easier for me to check new submissions frequently, I require projects to be zipped in a particular format. I will provide a program that checks whether your project passes these tests and then zips your project in the correct format. If a project submission is improperly zipped, is missing any tasks/deliverables, or does not pass the required test cases, then that submission will be marked as incomplete. You may resubmit the project as long as you follow the restrictions in the deadlines section below.
18.title: Project Submission

19.body: I don't like assigning deadlines for assignments unless there is a compelling reason that I need your work by a particular time or need to otherwise limit submissions. If I do set a deadline or other restriction, then I will explain why. The following restrictions apply to project submissions: You are allowed to submit Guided Project assignments as often as you like until 11:59 PM ET on Thursday, December 12th. You can submit up to one proposal for a Self-Directed Project or an alternative Expanded Project every week. You can submit up to one Self-Directed Project or Expanded Project (I'll refer to these as the open-ended projects) each week. If a project requires me to approve a proposal, then you cannot submit that project until the week after you submit the proposal. The cutoff for weekly proposal/project submissions is 11:59 PM ET on Sunday. If you submit after this time, then it will count as your submission for the following week. The last weekly proposal deadline is 11:59 PM ET on Sunday, December 1st. The last weekly project deadline is 11:59 PM ET on Thursday, December 12th. There is a small window in which I will accept late work: if you submit an assignment after the deadline but before I download the submissions from Blackboard, then I will count your submission as on time. I usually download submissions in the morning or early afternoon the day after the deadline and then close the link on Blackboard, but I do not make any guarantees for work submitted after a deadline. An open Blackboard link after the deadline does not mean your submission will be accepted, and I may download submissions at any time once the deadline has passed. Submitting after the deadline is always a gamble, and I do not recommend it. I will otherwise not accept any late submissions and will strictly enforce all deadlines. The deadline for Guided Projects and final weekly deadline for open-ended projects is your last opportunity to submit work for this class. My reasons for these restrictions: The Guided Project assignments can be fully checked by my test program and a couple of scripts, so they take little time for me to review. I leave myself a week at the end of the semester to determine final grades, review projects one last time, and resolve academic integrity cases. I chose to go with weekly project/proposal submissions instead of project-specific deadlines to keep the open-ended projects more flexible. The limit of one per week ensures I don't get flooded with too many late in the semester. I aim to review them within a week of the cut-off so you can have timely feedback. I give specific times and enforce deadlines strictly to ensure I handle assignment submissions consistently and fairly. It doesn't matter how close you are to a missed deadline or what excuse you offer. You either submit the assignment on time or arrange for an extension (see below); otherwise, I will not accept the assignment.
19.title: Deadlines

2.body: CSC110 and CSC110L share objectives. Upon successful completion of both courses, students should be able to: Discuss the challenges inherent in communicating with (programming) a (non-reasoning) computer. Break a complex problem down into smaller more manageable components. Provide step-by-step instructions to solve small computational problems. Using at least one programming language, write examples of and solve problems in programs with the following basic programming constructs and tools: Mathematical expressions Conditional expressions Simple iterative statements Simple functions Simple data structures, such as arrays, lists, and strings Discuss the importance of commenting and good code structure/style
2.title: Objectives

20.body: In rare cases (such as medical or family emergencies), I will allow an extension to a deadline or an exception to another restriction on submitting an assignment. You can email me to ask for a such an exception if you believe one is appropriate in your situation. Your email should include an explanation of why you need the extension, a new proposed deadline (or other proposed change to existing restrictions), and your current progress on the assignment. Be sure to send me your code and any other material you've created for the assignment so far. I have some expectations if I am going to give an extension or make an exception to a class policy: You've demonstrated that you read this policy by including all of the information I just asked for. If you're having trouble with the assignment, then you're taking steps to get help. Usually this means seeing a tutor or going to office hours. You are clearly making an effort to keep up with the class and not procrastinating. If there is an ongoing problem affecting your work or participation in the class and you want me to accommodate you, then you must let me know early and keep me informed as that situation develops. Extensions and other exceptions are given on a case-by-case basis. I will try to be as fair as possible, but this comes down to my judgement and whether you've been proactively communicating with me.
20.title: Extensions and Other Exceptions

21.body: If you struggle with deadlines or time management, then I'd like to offer some advice: Start your work early. You have four to six assignments to complete depending on your desired grade, and you probably won't be ready to start them for the first few weeks of class. It's not a big workload if you spread it out, but it will be overwhelming if you let it pile up towards the end of the semester. Deadlines in this class are not targets. If I give you a deadline, then this is the latest that I'm willing to accept the assignment under most circumstances. I expect you to finish and submit the assignment much earlier. If you plan to submit something the night it's due, then there's a good chance you'll miss that deadline. I can't stop you from taking this risk, but you have to accept the consequences if it doesn't work out. There are people you can talk to if you need help. Talk to someone when you start having trouble; don't wait until you feel hopelessly stuck or overwhelmed. And if you did wait until you were overwhelmed, that doesn't mean it's too late to get help! That just means it's even more urgent that you ask for help now , and that it may take more effort to catch up. I'm available by email and during office hours . The Learning Commons employs peer tutors who can help you with this class. Academic coaches can be reached by email and are available by appointment. They may not be able to help you with your code, but they're great to talk to if you have trouble with time management or adjusting to college. Keep backups of your work in case you have a problem with your computer. Google Drive and Dropbox both have free plans, and I believe you can use OneDrive for free through your QU account. You can also download any work you previously submitted on Blackboard.
21.title: Advice

While I may not deduct points from your grade if you miss these assignments, ignoring reading and practice assignments may result in you not acquiring the necessary skills and knowledge to complete the major projects, which means they can still indirectly affect your final grade. 23.body: This class uses a labor-based grading system. I don't expect most students to be familiar with labor-based grading, so before I get into our particular version, I'd like to introduce the concept and explain why we're using it.
23.title: Grading

24.body: Labor-based grading and contract grading are approaches to grading that try to emphasize the work you put into a class over the outcomes of that work. This grading system specifies what work you need to complete to earn a particular final grade, and individual assignments are not graded. You receive a final grade based on what work you complete rather than a weighted average of grades from assignments and exams. There are plenty of articles online about labor-based grading if you want to read about it in more detail. Here's one that was easy to find and that I think explains the concept well: https://cep.barnard.edu/labor-based-grading . This article also links to an example grade contract. My implementation will differ, but my goals are largely the same.
24.title: What is Labor-Based Grading?

25.body: The author of the example grade contract shown in the Bernard College webpage gives an excellent explanation of why they prefer contract grading over traditional grades. I recommend reading that if you want to hear more about the motivation behind labor-based grading. I'll try to summarize why I dislike traditional grading systems and think this system addresses some (but not all) of the problems with grades. Grades are not a good source of feedback. Grades provide little information on their own compared to comments and other qualitative feedback. Grades punish you for mistakes. Whether intended or not, low grades act as a punishment. Mistakes are a necessary part of the learning process, and you should not be penalized for them. Giving lower grades to indicate mistakes or areas for improvement is counterproductive. A laber-based grading system is more transparent than a weighted average. If you want a particular grade, then you know exactly which assignments you must complete for that grade.
25.title: Why Labor-Based Grading?

26.body: Previous versions of this syllabus required you to choose a final grade and submit a grade contract with the terms for that grade. After trying this a few times, I don't think requiring everyone to submit their own contract is worth the trouble. Instead, I've listed each possible grade along with the required work to earn that grade. At the end of the semester, you will receive the highest final grade for which you qualify. You qualify for a grade if you meet every requirement. For an A: Complete all Guided Project assignments (1.1, 1.2, 2.1, 2.2) Complete one Expanded Project assignment (1.3, 2.3) For a B: Complete all Guided Project assignments (1.1, 1.2, 2.1, 2.2) For a C: Complete three of the four Guided Project assignments (1.1, 1.2, 2.1, 2.2) For a D: Complete two of the four Guided Project assignments (1.1, 1.2, 2.1, 2.2) For an F: Don't meet the requirements for any of the above grades The Self-Directed Project can be used to replace an Expanded Project or a pair of Guided Projects. You can complete multiple Self-Directed Projects to replace additional assignments.
26.title: The Grading System

27.body: If I'm not graded on an assignment, does that mean I don't need to put any effort into it? I review assignments and check that they were completed as directed. Not receiving a grade on your assignment doesn't mean you don't have to do any work or put effort into your work. You should still expect these assignments to challenge you and require a significant amount of work. Why can't I get an A+? QU's grading system does not include an A+. The highest grade you can earn in any QU class is an A. Why can't I get an A-, B+, B-, C+, or C-? I don't see a reason to include an option for every in-between grade. An A is the highest grade you can earn, a B is less demanding but good grade, and a C represents the minimum requirements to pass this class and take more CSC/SER courses. Is there extra credit? There is no extra credit, but there are multiple ways to meet the requirements for any grade contract. You can replace anything with a Self-Directed Project, and you can propose alternative versions of Expanded Projects. Can I get partial credit on an assignment? There is no partial credit for late or incomplete assignments. You must complete the entire assignment, submit it on time, and submit it in the correct format to receive credit for it. If you're having trouble, then please ask me or a tutor for help. Are there exams? Graded exams, quizzes, and similar assessments don't work with this grading system. There are no exams, not even a final exam. However, I may give ungraded quizzes as a way for you to check your understanding of topics we've covered. If you have questions about the grading system that aren't answered here, then please don't hesitate to ask me about it! I want you to feel comfortable with the grading system and understand what's required to earn the grade you want.
27.title: FAQ

3.body: There are a few reasons that I may update this syllabus: The majority of students and I have agreed to change a policy during the first week of class. Parts of this syllabus are negotiable, and I will mention these during our first class. A policy is not working as intended or a problem with the syllabus comes up later in the semester. For example, if a project was due in the middle of the semester and we had not covered the necessary topics before it was due. I need to correct a mistake in the syllabus, such as a broken link or inaccurate information about an assignment or policy. If the syllabus needs to be revised, then any changes will be noted here. I will also keep older versions of the syllabus available on Blackboard so that there is a clear record of all changes. (2024/11/15) Updates to project submission/late policy, project deadlines, and final grade requirements. I forgot to update the syllabus earlier in the semester to explicitly state how much leeway I allow for late submissions. This was announced a while ago, but the syllabus didn't reflect that change until now. The changes to project deadlines announced last week have now been added to the syllabus. These allow for a few more open-ended project submissions and a later final cutoff for all project submissions (12/12 instead of 12/8). Most significantly, the requirements for each final grade have been reduced. I'll list the reasons for that change here so I don't need to put them all in a long announcement email. Fall 2024 is my third iteration on the current set of assignments and the labor-based grading system used in this syllabus. When reviewing the syllabus in preparation for the spring semester, I was leaning towards reducing the number of required projects. While it is late in the semester, I don't think it's too late to make that change in this class. These new requirements match what I plan to use in spring 2025. Late changes can be disruptive, but in this case I don't think it will negatively effect many, if any, students. You either have one less required project to earn your anticipated grade, or you can finish the same amount of work you previously planned on doing and get a significantly higher grade. I'm not aware of anyone who has finished the new requirements for an A and begun working on the last project required under the old syllabus, so I'm hoping this won't make anyone feel as though some of their work has been invalidated. We covered the required topics for some projects later than I expected, and I think my recommended project schedule for an A pushes too high a workload towards the end of the semester. It's perhaps not an unreasonable amount of work, but I don't like asking students in an intro class to complete two large and challenging assignments during the last 4-5 weeks of the semester. Project 2.1 covers arrays and iteration. While I would prefer students get more practice with these topics than 2.1 offers, I still think 3 guided projects is a reasonable minimum for a passing grade that allows you to take more CSC/SER classes. In summary: the new requirements lower the workload for students, should not negatively impact students despite how late in the semester they were implemented, and still require students to engage with all of the learning objectives to pass with a C or better.

32.body: Here is a link to Quinnipiac University's Academic Integrity (AI) policy: https://catalog.qu.edu/university-policies/academic-integrity-policy/ . This policy applies to all courses at QU, and this part of the syllabus goes into detail about how the AI policy works in our class. From this point forward I will assume you are familiar with the school's AI policy.
32.title: Academic Integrity (AI) Policy

33.body: I consider it important that you can freely discuss assignments with other students. Your peers can be an excellent source of help and feedback, and your own insights and feedback can greatly help other students. I don't want the school's or my AI policies to discourage you from talking to anyone else about your work. Therefore, this section serves as my explicit written permission to do the following: You may share work you create for this class with anybody, including your classmates, and publicly post this work online. You may discuss assignments from this class with anybody. You may ask anybody for help with these assignments and view their work if they are willing to share it with you. In summary, you own all the work you do for this class, and that means you decide what to do with it. However, I need to clarify that this permission does not extend to the following actions, all of which directly violate the school's AI policy: You may not share work or post it publicly for the purpose of helping someone else violate the school's AI policy. This includes if somebody asks you for your work and informs you that they plan to copy it before you share the work with them. See the section on "Facilitation and Collusion" in the school's AI policy. You may not copy your work from other people or from a large language model (an "artificial intelligence" program). I'll cover this in more detail in a later section. I do not consider you responsible for anyone's misuse of material that you shared in good faith. I will always take your word regarding how you intended or expected your work to be used unless I have strong evidence that contradicts you.
33.breadcrumbs: Academic Integrity » Permission to Share and Discuss Work
33.title: Permission to Share and Discuss Work

34.body: First and most important: in any situation where you have doubts or are unsure whether an action would violate this policy, ask me! It's always okay to ask whether you can do something. This section exists for two reasons: to make it easier for someone who has genuine questions to determine whether an action qualifies as cheating, and to give me something to point to if somebody claims they didn't know their actions qualified as cheating. Going through a series of flimsy excuses is one of the most tedious parts of handling an AI violation, so I'd like to be thorough here and save myself some trouble later. This will focus on plagiarism on programming assignments. I'll use the phrase " other work " to refer to any work that was created by somebody other than you or by an LLM (such as ChatGPT). The following actions will nearly always violate the AI policy: Copying other work in whole or in part, whether by copying the file, copying and pasting the file's contents, or viewing the file and retyping the same information by hand. Modifying other work after copying it, whether to disguise the copying or "make it your own" (an excuse I've heard frequently) does not change the fact that it was copied. What matters is that you copied work, not how you copied it or what you did before or after copying it. Paraphrasing other work in whole or in part. As far as I'm concerned, this is the same as copying. In my experience, some paraphrasing is often used to disguise that work was copied, and the claim that work was paraphrased is used as an excuse to deny having copied work. Using other work as a reference when creating your own work. This normally results in copying or paraphrasing as described above, but I mention it because it's another common excuse used to explain evidence of copying. Doing your work under the direction of another person. It's okay to talk to someone about your work while you're working, but it's not okay to let them dictate the code to you. If you're mostly writing what someone else tells you to write, then you are not doing your own work. Try talking to them about your problem, taking some notes, and then fixing the problem on your own. Exceptions to the above: You can use material that I intentionally provide you (such as my notes, starter code, assignment descriptions, or examples from class) with or without modification in your own work for this class. You don't need to document your use of such material because it is expected and obvious from context. If you want to copy or paraphrase from another source, then you can as long as you do the following: Discuss it with me first and get my permission to use the other work on the assignment. Clearly state which outside sources you used and provide a reliable link or other means to access those sources. Clearly show what was taken from the other source and what is your own original work. Two general rules I use if someone appears to have plagiarized but claims they did not: If large sections of your code are identical or nearly identical to existing code, then it isn't your work. If you are writing your own code and following the guidelines I provide in this policy, then you should always end up with significantly different code on all but the simplest programs. If you don't understand your code and cannot explain how it works, then it isn't your work. You should not be using code that you don't understand, and you are not going to accidentally write a working program that solves a specific problem without some understanding of the code you're writing. If your code doesn't appear to be something a student realistically would have written and you cannot explain how it works, then I will not accept it for an assignment.
34.breadcrumbs: Academic Integrity » What Counts as Plagiarism?
34.title: What Counts as Plagiarism?

35.body: If you are retaking this class, then I expect you to complete every assignment from scratch without reusing any of your old work. I consider reusing work from the last time you took this class equivalent to reusing work you completed for a different class ("double-dipping" in QU's AI policy).
35.breadcrumbs: Academic Integrity » Retaking this Class and Self-Plagiarism
35.title: Retaking this Class and Self-Plagiarism

36.body: You're free to discuss assignments with LLMs such as ChatGPT, but I do not recommend using them for this class. While we might colloquially refer to an LLM as an "artificial intelligence," these tools are not intelligent and do not understand the conversation they are having with you. They are complex algorithms running on powerful hardware, and they are very good at one thing: using their training data to produce text that looks like something a human might write in the context of your conversation. LLMs are prone to hallucinating (making up false information), and they do not know when they are hallucinating. These tools are most useful in the hands of an expert who can critically evaluate the information generated by an LLM. You are most likely not an expert at this point. As mentioned earlier, I treat material generated by an LLM the same as material created by another person for the purpose of this AI policy. It is not your work, and using this material in an assignment violates this policy. If you are using ChatGPT for help with an assignment, then please save that conversation so you can share it with me or the AI Office if your work is called into question. This is an easy way to establish whether you used the tool appropriately, and if you cannot or will not provide that evidence then I will not give you the benefit of the doubt.
36.title: ChatGPT and LLMs

37.body: Consequences for AI violations are determined either by joint resolution, case review, or a hearing. In a joint resolution, you and I must agree to any proposed consequences, and in a case review or hearing I will still be consulted about appropriate consequences. This section covers what I believe are appropriate consequences on a first offense for most AI violations. If you plagiarize, cheat, or otherwise violate the AI policy on an assignment, then under no circumstances will I consider it appropriate to give you credit for the assignment. This is not a punishment for cheating, it is simply enforcing the requirements of the grading system. If you copied or cheated on even a small portion of the assignment, then you did not complete the entire assignment ; you completed some of the assignment and then copied the remaining work. To give any credit, full or partial, would be a reward for cheating. In addition to enforcing the normal penalty for incomplete work, I consider the following consequences to be appropriate: If you cheat on one assignment, then your final grade should be reduced by one letter grade after accounting for the incomplete assignment. I will not allow you to redo the assignment, but you may replace the assignment with a Self-Directed Project if there is enough time remaining. If there isn't enough time to complete a Self-Directed Project, then I will not give you an extension. If you cheat on multiple assignments, then you should receive a final grade of F. Depending on the extent or nature of this cheating (for example, if you cheat on more than two assignments), further penalties may be appropriate.
37.breadcrumbs: Academic Integrity » Consequences for AI Violations
37.title: Consequences for AI Violations

38.body: The lab is a separate class from the lecture. I do not have any lab sections this semester, so if you're reading this then you should just have me for the lecture. However, there are still a few things I want to mention about the lab: You receive a separate final grade in the lab, and it may differ from your final grade in this class. Only your work for the lecture affects your grade in the lecture, and only your work in the lab affects your grade in the lab. Passing one class doesn't guarantee you'll pass the other. The lab has a separate Blackboard page and syllabus. Make sure you're on the correct Blackboard page when submitting assignments or looking for class material.

5.body: I am a part-time faculty member and do not have an office on campus, but I can meet in person after my last CSC110 class ends at 3:15 on Tuesday/Thursday. You can meet me in CCE 030 between 3:15 and 3:45, and if we need to stay later then we can move to the modular unit on the second floor of CCE. I normally end office hours once all students have left. Please send me an email ahead of time if you plan to arrive after 3:30; otherwise, I may not still be there when you show up. We can also schedule a remote meeting on a different day if my in-person time doesn't work for you. If you'd like to meet remotely, then please send me an email with your availability over the next 2-3 days. I'll try to find a time that works for both of us and schedule a Zoom meeting.

6.body: I will post or link to all course material and assignments on Blackboard. If you want to find something or submit an assignment, go to our Blackboard site and look in the appropriate page. If you think I forgot to post something, then send me an email and I'll either post it or tell you where to find it.
6.title: Blackboard

7.body: My email is zckohlberg@qu.edu . I check my email most weekdays and try to respond to all emails within 24 hours. If you email me after Friday morning or on the weekend, then I probably won't see it until Monday. You're still welcome to email me at any time. I will answer most questions via email if you don't want to ask in person. If you're asking for help with an assignment, coding issue, or software, then please attach your code (the text file, not a screenshot). Try to include as much relevant information as possible and be specific about what you want to know. This helps me give you a useful answer more quickly. If you want me to do something more involved than answer a few questions, such as review your code or help you debug a program, then you should meet with me during office hours. I'm happy to help you with coding, debugging, and other tasks as long as you're the one doing the task. You should not come to office hours or send an email expecting me to do your work for you.
7.title: Email

9.body: I may hold class remotely via Zoom if I cannot attend the meeting in person (for example, if I'm sick). If I need to cancel class, then I will notify everyone as early as possible in a Blackboard announcement.
